Chapter 6 — Visibility Leakage

Why Managers Discover Problems Too Late

Revenue problems rarely appear overnight.

They build quietly.

A deal sits untouched for two weeks.

A follow-up is missed.

A high-value opportunity loses momentum.

A customer stops engaging.

Individually, these signals don't seem alarming.

But by the time they appear in a weekly pipeline review or monthly forecast, the damage has already been done.

This is Visibility Leakage.

What is Visibility Leakage?

Visibility Leakage occurs when critical revenue signals exist within the business but remain invisible to the people responsible for making decisions.

The data is available.

The insight isn't.

As a result, managers react to problems instead of preventing them.

